player.seasonOutlook: Huerter found a home with the Kings last season after spending his first four seasons with the Hawks. Huerter benefitted from playing with two strong playmakers in De'Aaron Fox and Domantas Sabonis, and parlayed it into career best marks of 15.2 PPG (48.5 FG%) and 2.7 3PG (40.2 3P%). The Kings have a high-powered offense that maximizes the open looks, ideal for a knock-down shooter like Huerter.

Gafford has solid potential on defense and is a high-efficiency finisher on offense, and with Kristaps Porzingis out of town should have a chance to full-time start for the Wizards. In 47 starts last season, Gafford averaged 10.8 PPG on 73.0 F%, 6.4 RPG, 1.4 BPG and 0.5 SPG in only 24.7 MPG. If he edges that up closer to 30 MPG, he has nightly double-double upside that sneaks him into the top-100 of fantasy hoops rankings.

After playing for four teams in his first eight seasons, Grant has found a home in Portland with the Trail Blazers. He averaged 20.5 PPG with a career-high 2.3 3PG last season, and parlayed that strong campaign into a big contract extension this summer. This makes Grant the starting power forward for the Trail Blazers as they move into their youth movement, giving a veteran presence and consistent shooting/scoring production. He enters the season as a top-100 fantasy basketball prospect, good value in the later part of drafts.

McConnell continues to be an intriguing fantasy option for managers in deeper formats. He appeared in 75 games last season, starting six. McConnell averaged 8.7 PPG, 5.3 APG, 3.1 RPG and 1.1 SPG while shooting 54.3% from the floor, including a career best 44.1% from beyond the arc. Heâ€™ll be competing for backcourt minutes behind Tyrese Haliburton, Bennedict Mathurin and Buddy Hield, and provides managers in category formats with a high field goal percentage along with consistent assists and steals.

Conley began last season as a veteran with diminishing prospects on a rebuilding Jazz team, but once traded to the Timberwolves midseason he showed he still had some gas left in the tank. In 24 games with the Timberwolves, Conley averaged 14.0 PPG, 5.0 APG, 3.1 RPG, 2.4 3PG and 1.2 SPG in 31.4 MPG. Conley could produce similar numbers in a similar role this season, but be aware that he will be 36 years old this season and has dealt with injury that has cost him extended periods in four of the last six seasons.

Brogdon has had an action-packed year. He was traded from the Pacers, where he had started and averaged more than 20 PPG, to come off the bench for the Celtics. But he parlayed solid production off the bench into the NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award, playing a key role for the Celtics before injuries felled him in the playoffs. This offseason, Brogdon was dealt to Portland, where he will be a veteran presence in a young backcourt that no longer has Damian Lillard. Barring another trade, expect Brogdon to put up similar numbers to last season in the Rose City.

Fantasy managers may be worried about Thompsonâ€™s durability, but he played in 69 games last season. He averaged 21.4 PPG, 4.1 RPG and 2.4 APG in 33.1 MPG. In addition, he hit 4.4 triples per game, a career high. Thompson's shooting has returned to pre-injury levels and fantasy managers can expect a similar statistical output from him this season. The offseason addition of Chris Paul should create additional catch and shoot opportunities for Thompson in the final year of his contract.

Gordon looked comfortable on both ends of the court with the Nuggets last season, putting up 16.3 PPG, 6.6 RPG, 3.0 APG, 0.8 SPG and 0.8 BPG while shooting a career high 56.4% from the field. Since the Nuggets' rotation has minimal changes outside of Bruce Brownâ€™s departure, Gordon should play similar minutes this season. His 61% free throw percentage is the only blemish on Gordonâ€™s fantasy resume heading into 2023-2024.

The two biggest assets Looney brings to your fantasy team are rebounds and field goal percentage. He led the league in offensive rebounds (274) and averaged a career-high 9.3 rebounds per game last season. Looney also averaged 7.0 PPG, 2.5 APG, 0.6 SPG and 0.6 BPG in 23.9 MPG. For two consecutive regular seasons, the Warriors' big man has played every game. It's possible that Chris Paul's arrival will force Looney to the bench, but either way, he'll be an important part of the Warriors' rotation. His 2023-2024 season will most likely look eerily similar statistically to his 2022-2023 season, making him a solid target late in fantasy drafts.

Green has consistently been a top-100 player his lengthy NBA career. The veteran forward averaged 8.5 PPG, 7.2 RPG, 6.8 APG, 1.0 SPG and 0.8 BPG in 31.5 MPG last season and also shot a career high 52.7% from the field. Heâ€™s the only player to average 5.0 RPG, 5.0 APG, 1.0 BPG and 1 SPG since blocks and steals were tracked during the 1973-1974 season. His defensive numbers are on the decline, which is not surprising since he is now 33 years old, but Green remains a reliable fantasy option, especially in category formats.

Victor Wembanyama will get a lot of attention this season, but don't discount Miller as he's one of the few rookies who could start right away. Miller averaged 18.8 PPG, 8.2 RPG, 2.1 APG 0.9 SPG and 0.9 BPG at Alabama in 2022â€“23. Despite an underwhelming Summer League performance, Miller fits the Hornets roster well. In Charlotte's rotation, Miller will compete with Miles Bridges, P.J. Washington and Gordon Hayward for minutes, and he could provide managers with a solid source of points, rebounds and steals.

As a rookie last season, Williams demonstrated an intriguing set of skills that should serve him well going forward. In 17 starts, Williams averaged 11.6 PPG, 10.0 RPG and 1.1 BPG in 27.0 MPG. His size stands out on both sides of the court, standing 7-foot-1 with a remarkable 7-foot-7 wingspan, measurements that few players in the league can approach or match. Williams should be a solid contributor as a scorer and rebounder in his second NBA season, and has the potential to finish as a top-100 fantasy option when you factor in his high FG%.

Oubre signed a one-year deal with the 76ers and is a good addition to their roster. He's also someone worth taking a shot on late in fantasy drafts. Oubre averaged 20.3 PPG, 5.2 RPG, 1.1 APG and 1.4 SPG last season with the Hornets. Starting 40 of his 48 games, he shot 43.1% from the field and attempted 17.1 field goals per game, a career high. He won't be able to repeat that on this 76ers team, but Oubre has a chance to emerge as a key role player.

Reid is coming off the best season of his career. He averaged 11.5 PPG, 4.9 RPG, 1.1 APG and 0.8 BPG in 68 games, logging 18.4 MPG. While Karl-Anthony Towns was out for 52 games with a severely strained right calf muscle, Reid's production increased when given a chance to start. Reid averaged 16.5 PPG, 7.0 RPG, 1.8 APG, 1.4 SPG and 1.0 BPG in 11 starts. As a result of his new contract this summer, Reid will continue to play a key role in the Timberwolves rotation. Keep Reid on your waiver wire speed dial if Towns or Rudy Gobert miss time.

After a back injury derailed Porterâ€™s previous season, he played in a career-high 62 games on his way to a NBA championship in 2022-23. He averaged 17.4 PPG and 5.5 RPG while shooting 49% from the field. With few changes to the Nuggets roster this season, the 25 year old should maintain a similar role in the teamâ€™s rotation. While durability remains a concern, Porter is an excellent source of points and 3-pointers whenever he's on the court.

It is fair to say that Hart is a jack of all trades on this Knicks team. In 25 games after being traded to New York, he averaged 10.2 PPG, 7.0 RPG, 3.6 APG, 1.4 SPG and 0.5 BPG. Hart signed a massive contract extension which means heâ€™ll play ample minutes on this Knicks team. One of the top rebounding guards in the game, Hart is a great value at his average draft position in points and category formats.

Williams has emerged as one of the best defensive big men in the league. The biggest concern remains his durability; he was limited to 35 games last season due to knee surgery and averaged 8.0 PPG, 5.4 RPG and 1.4 BPG in 23.5 MPG. Now in Portland, the veteran big man will pair with Deandre Ayton in the new-look Trail Blazers frontcourt, with a possible bump in fantasy value compared to his days in Boston.

Ivey's rookie season was mixed, but Detroit lacked cohesion after Cade Cunningham went down with a shin injury. The No. 5 pick in the 2022 NBA Draft averaged 16.3 PPG, 5.2 APG and 3.9 RPG in 31.1 MPG. Ivey shot 41.6% from the floor and averaged 3.2 turnovers per game. Reducing his turnovers and developing a more consistent jumper would help improve his fantasy value. Despite sharing the backcourt with Cunningham, Killian Hayes and rookie Ausar Thompson, Ivey is still expected to play a similar number of minutes. He's a player to target late in fantasy drafts.

Smith in a great position to make a second-year leap and finish inside the top 100 this season. Ime Udoka is his new coach and Fred VanVleet and Dillon Brooks are his new veteran teammates. In his rookie season, Smith averaged 12.8 PPG and 7.2 RPG while shooting 41% from the floor. Smith shined in the Summer League and is trending up as he enters his second NBA season with an improved supporting cast.

Sexton arrived at the Jazz alongside Lauri Markkanen in the Donovan Mitchell trade, initially seen as the more valuable piece. However, injuries and a breakout season by Markkanen shifted perceptions. Sexton played a career low 23.9 minutes per game in just 48 games. The soon-to-be 25 year old settled for averages of 14.3 PPG, 2.2 RPG and 2.9 APG while shooting 50.6% from the floor. This season, he has to prove he stay on the floor and play at a high level on a consistent basis. Surrounded by solid backcourt players like Jordan Clarkson, Talen Horton-Tucker, Kris Dunn and rookie Keyonte George, the competition at guard is intense but Sexton is worth a late-round pick.

Sharpe entered the NBA as perhaps the most talented player in the 2022 NBA draft, but he had no post-high school experience and was considered very raw. He got a lot of playing time as a rookie and it started paying off down the stretch of the season, after the Trail Blazers shut down Damian Lillard and went into plan-for-the-future mode. He started the last 10 games of the season and averaged 23.7 PG (46.0 FG%, 37.8 3P%, 77.3 FT%), 6.1 RPG, 4.1 APG and 3.1 3PG in 35.9 MPG. He isnâ€™t expected to get nearly that volume to start this season, but the talent is there and his upside is strong if he earns a larger role as the season progresses.

Despite playing on a Celtics team with a deep rotation, White was a borderline top-100 player last season. He played in all 82 games and averaged 12.4 PPG, 3.6 RPG, 3.9 APG, 0.7 SPG and 0.9 BPG in 28.3 MPG while shooting a solid 46.2% from the floor. With Marcus Smart traded to the Memphis Grizzlies over the offseason, White is a legitimate breakout candidate. Last season, he averaged 15.4 PPG, 4.3 RPG, 5.1 APG, 0.8 SPG, and 1.0 BPG in 21 games without Smart, and his ability to contribute to multiple statistical areas makes him more valuable in category formats.

Donovan Mitchell's acquisition before training camp changed LeVert's role in Cleveland. He often shifted in and out of the starting lineup and faced varying roles, from primary creator to off-ball player. Despite these challenges, LeVert averaged 12.1 PPG and 3.9 APG, displaying growth in his role as the season progressed. LeVert's playmaking and defense also improved, making him an essential part of the Cavaliersâ€™ rotation. This offseason, Cleveland added Max Strus and Georges Niang, who will cut into LeVert's playing time. With that in mind, LeVert is likely to be more of a streaming option this season.

Okongwu was valuable in category formats last season despite coming off the bench (9.9 PPG, 7.2 RPG and 1.3 BPG in 23.1 minutes per game). A solid rebounder and shot blocker, Okongwu also shot 64% from the floor in 2022-23, and fantasy managers could get elite production out of him if Capela is traded or misses action at any point in the season.

Anderson has finished as a top 100 fantasy player in three of his last six seasons. He excelled in the Timberwolvesâ€™ frontcourt with Karl-Anthony Towns missing most of the season (9.4 PPG, 5.3 RPG, 4.9 APG, 1.1 SPG and 1.0 BPG in 28.4 MPG). Even with Anthony-Towns healthy, Rudy Gobert back, and Naz Reid back in the mix, Anderson will still be an important part of Minnesota's rotation, but he won't have the upside he had last year. With the right expectations, the play-making forward is a fine target in the later rounds.

Schroder averaged 12.6 PPG, 2.5 RPG, 4.5 APG and 0.8 SPG in 30.0 MPG with the Lakers last season. He signed a two-year contract with the Raptors over the summer and is projected for 30+ minutes per game in Toronto. As a solid source of points, assists and steals, Schroder should also be on your radar late in your fantasy draft.

Since Cade Cunningham missed nearly the entire season, Bogdanovic became one of the Pistons' top scoring options. He averaged a team-high and career-high 21.6 PPG, 3.8 RPG and 2.6 APG while shooting 49% from the floor. Bogdanovic will have a tough time replicating this statistical production with Cunningham healthy and Joe Harris, Monte Morris and rookie Ausar Thompson entering the mix. Still, the efficient veteran is a reliable source of points and 3-pointers and a nice puzzle piece to fantasy rosters.

Fultz was arguably the Magicâ€™s best point guard last season, averaging a career high 14.0 PPG, 3.9 RPG, 5.7 APG and 1.2 SPG in 29.6 MPG. The 60 games he played in was the second highest single-season total of his career. He finished as a top 100 player and, along with Paolo Banchero and Franz Wagner, will be an integral part of the Magic's future. Although Fultz is the favorite to be named Orlando's starting point guard, Anthony Black was drafted No. 6 overall by the Magic in the draft. Fultz is a great source of assists and steals, so don't hesitate to select him if he falls in your draft.

In 28.5 minutes per game last season, Zubac averaged a career high 10.8 PPG, 10.0 RPG and 1.3 BPG. The question is whether he can keep putting up those numbers with Mason Plumlee now in the fold. The defensive versatility of Plumlee allowed him to occasionally provide a bit more stability than Zubac in the middle. Plumlee's offensive skill set gives him an edge as well. He reads the floor better and is a better passer than Zubac. In addition, he has better shooting splits from the floor and the line. Zubac is a solid late-round pick, but these are some things to keep in mind.

The last two seasons, Barrett has ranked just outside the top-200. In 73 games last year, he averaged 19.6 PPG, 5.0 RPG and 2.8 APG. In terms of defensive stats, Barrett doesn't offer much to fantasy managers. Additionally, he is an inconsistent shooter and below average passer. Barrett should remain part of the Knicks rotation, but you shouldn't reach on him in fantasy drafts.

Thompson is making the transition from Overtime Elite competition to the NBA, so it can be challenging to predict how he'll perform in his rookie season. He averaged 16.3 PPG, 6.4 RPG, 6.2 APG and 2.4 SPG in 28 MPG last season for the City Reapers. Considering Thompson was selected No. 4 overall in the draft, he should earn minutes sooner rather than later, especially with Kevin Porter Jr. no longer in Houston's plans. It is a good idea to target Thompson late in your fantasy draft.

While the Nets faced a lot of drama during the 2022-2023 season, O'Neale was one of the team's most dependable role players. He played in 76 games and led the Nets in minutes and averaged 8.8 PPG, 3.7 APG and shot 38.9% on 5.5 three-point attempts per game, all career highs. He also displayed improved ball-handling skills and had 23 games with five or more assists. Although it remains to be seen what O'Neale's role will be with the Nets this season, he's expected to again provide a steady source of 3-pointers, assists and defensive stats.

Last season solidified Robinsonâ€™s status as one of the rising centers in the league. He averaged 7.4 PPG, 9.4 RPG, 1.0 APG, 1.0 SPG and 2.0 BPG in 27.0 MPG. Given Robinson's circumstance with the Knicks heading into this season, it isn't out of the question that he replicates last season's performance. He's a great rebounder and shot-blocker, but his low free throw percentage should be kept in mind.

In this crowded backcourt with many young options, Anthony will have to share minutes in 2023-24. In 29.6 minutes per game last season, Anthony averaged 14.0 PPG, 3.9 RPG, 5.7 APG,and 1.2 SPG and showed toughness with the ball in his hands. Because Anthony has only played 20 or more games twice in his career, the perception is that he is injury prone. He'll have to shake that to be a big fantasy contributor this season.

Melton finished as a top 100 fantasy player last season. During his 77 games, he started 58 and averaged 10.1 PPG, 4.1 RPG, 2.6 APG and 1.6 SPG. If James Harden is traded, Melton's fantasy value gets a bump for this season.

Jonesâ€™ ability to contribute to multiple statistical categories positions him as key option in category formats. Last season, he averaged 10.0 PPG, 4.1 RPG, 2.5 APG and 1.6 SPG in 29.6 MPG. With Trey Murphy III expected to sidelined early in the season after injuring the meniscus in his left knee, Jones should be on your radar in most leagues.

During his 26 games with the Lakers last season, Vanderbilt averaged 7.2 PPG, 6.7 RPG and 1.2 SPG while shooting 56% from the field. Heâ€™s a versatile player who can guard the 1-4 positions. Vanderbilt has just signed a four-year, $48 million extension and hopes to prove he is capable of impacting the game heavily on both ends of the court. If you need to address the categories mentioned above, he's someone to keep on your radar in the later rounds, but Vanderbilt will have little impact elsewhere.

Considering Simmons' injury history and off-court concerns, drafting him onto your fantasy basketball team carries a great deal of risk. He averaged 7.0 PPG, 6.3 RPG, 6.1 APG and 1.3 SPG in 26.3 minutes last season. Nearly 90% of Simmons' field goal attempts were within 10 feet of the rim, and he wasn't taking jump shots. He was also limited to 42 games due to back issues. Simmons is not going to provide your fantasy team with a ton of points, but does contribute in other statistical areas. He's an intriguing bounce-back candidate who may be worth drafting in the later rounds if he's healthy.

Eason is poised for a breakout season. In 21.5 minutes per game in 2022-23, he averaged 9.3 PPG, 6.0 RPG, 1.1 APG and 1.2 SPG. He also played in all 82 games. Easonâ€™s contributions in rebounds and defensive categories are highly coveted by fantasy managers, so he's worth targeting late in drafts even with Dillon Brooks added to the Rockets roster. Eason should excel in new coach Ime Udokaâ€™s scheme.

Barnes rarely misses games but he is coming off his worst fantasy season in years. In 82 games last season, he averaged 15.0 PPG, 4.6 RPG, and 1.6 APG. The Kings didnâ€™t make any major changes during the offseason, and Barnes' statistical production should look eerily similar to last season. While he's a decent fantasy option at his average draft position, I wouldn't recommend reaching for him at this stage in his career.

Olynyk averaged a career high 28.6 MPG in 68 games for a rebuilding Jazz team last season, putting up 13.2 PPG, 6.2 RPG, 3.7 APG and 1.0 SPG. The Jazz are unlikely to have Olynyk play such a high number of minutes behind starter Walker Kessler this upcoming season since they drafted Taylor Hendricks and traded for John Collins. Olynyk is not someone you should aggressively target in fantasy drafts.

The Pistons will be counting on Duren to continue his development in their frontcourt, which also boasts Isaiah Stewart, James Wiseman and Marvin Bagley III. With Wiseman and Bagley vying for a backup role, Duren is expected to start after putting up 9.1 PPG, 9.0 RPG and 1.0 BPG in 25.0 MPG as a rookie last season. When Duren played 30 or more minutes per game in 2022-23, his averages increased to 14.2 PPG, 13.6 RPG, and 1.1 BPG. He's one to target in fantasy drafts.

The Clippers expect Powell to remain their sixth man, and he thrived in that role last season (17.0 PPG, 2.9 RPG and 1.8 APG). He a solid source of points and 3-pointers and is worth streaming into your lineup whenever Paul George or Kawhi Leonard are out.

Horford provides fantasy managers with a reasonable floor late in fantasy drafts and has a high ceiling due to an expanded role if Kristap Porzingis is injured. In 30.5 MPG last season, Horford averaged 10.0 PPG, 6.2 RPG, 3.0 APG and 1.0 BPG. Don't forget about the veteran big man late in your draft.

Quickley was a key reserve for the Knicks last season and the runner-up for Sixth Man of the Year. He finished just outside the top 100 in category formats. In the final 25 games of the regular season, Quickley averaged 20.2 PPG, 4.5 RPG, 4.0 APG and 1.3 SPG, an indicator of the type of fantasy potential he possesses.

Last season in 25 games with the Hawks, Bey averaged 11.6 PPG, 4.8 RPG and 1.4 APG in 25.2 MPG. He should have a chance to improve on those per game averages with John Collins now on the Jazz. Better in points leagues than category leagues, Bey will not contribute many defensive stats to your fantasy team but he's a good late-round pick since Quin Snyder's scheme is excellent for him.
